What I Learned

1. HTML Tags

HTML is made of tags that tell the browser how to display content
Most tags have an opening and closing tag: <p>text</p>
Some tags are self-closing: <br> <img> <hr>


2. Boilerplate Code

Every HTML file starts with the same basic structure
<!DOCTYPE html> tells the browser this is HTML5
<head> contains meta information — not visible on page
<body> contains everything the user sees


3. Lists

Unordered list <ul> — shows bullet points
Ordered list <ol> — shows numbers
Each item inside uses <li> tag


4. Attributes

Attributes give extra information to HTML tags
Written inside the opening tag
Format: attribute="value"
Example: <a href="https://CSK.com">Click here</a>


5. Image Element

<img> tag displays images — self-closing, no closing tag needed
src attribute — where the image is located
alt attribute — describes the image for accessibility
Every image must have an alt attribute


6. Inline vs Block Elements

Block elements take full width and start on a new line

Examples: <div> <p> <h1> <ul>


Inline elements only take as much space as their content

Examples: <span> <a> <strong> <img>


Rule: cannot put a block element inside an inline element


7. Div

Generic block container with no meaning on its own
Used to group elements together for layout or styling
Think of it as a box that holds other elements


8. HR Tag

<hr> stands for Horizontal Rule
Draws a horizontal line across the page
Self-closing — used to visually separate sections


9. Semantic Tags

Tags that clearly describe their meaning
Examples: <header> <footer> <nav> <main> <section> <article> <aside>
<div> and <span> are non-semantic — they describe nothing


10. Sub and Super

<sub> — subscript, appears below the normal line — example: H₂O
<sup> — superscript, appears above the normal line — example: 10²


11. Semantic Markup

Writing HTML that describes the meaning of content
Helps search engines understand your page (SEO)
Helps screen readers for visually impaired users
Bad practice: using <div> for everything
Good practice: <nav> for navigation, <article> for blog posts, <footer> for footer


12. HTML Entities

Special characters written as &name; so HTML does not misread them
&lt; →
&gt; → >
&amp; → &
&copy; → ©
&nbsp; → non-breaking space


13. Emmets

Shortcut system built into VS Code for writing HTML faster
Type the shortcut then press Tab to expand
! → full boilerplate
ul>li*3 → ul with 3 li items
h1+p → h1 followed by p
.container → <div class="container"></div>


Mistakes I Made Today

Forgot to add alt attribute on image tags
Confused inline and block elements initially
Used <div> everywhere instead of semantic tags

How I Fixed Them

Rule: every <img> must always have an alt attribute
Rule: starts on new line → block. Flows with text → inline
Rule: content has meaning → semantic tag. Just a container → div

Reflection
HTML is the skeleton of every webpage. It does not make things look good —
that is CSS. But without proper structure nothing else works correctly.
The most important lesson today was semantic markup — writing HTML that
means something, not just HTML that works.
